#: data/royale/buildings.ruleset:2165
msgid "Hal Saflieni Hypogeum"
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/buildings.ruleset:2182
msgid ""
"Ħal Saflieni Hypogeum is thought to have been a sanctuary and necropolis. It "
"pre-dates the Bronze Age and was one of the first, if not the first, shrines "
"built. With this wonder, the city having it will get +6 additional luxury "
"good points. The effect of this very early wonder ends with the invention of "
"bronze working. "
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/buildings.ruleset:2228
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"Allows you to choose any government, including those that have not yet been "
"researched by your civilization. It also allows unprovoked declaration of "
"war regardless of any senate instituted by a Democracy or Federation "
"government or by the United Nations."
msgstr "يسمح الفوضوية."

#: data/royale/cities.ruleset:58 data/sandbox/cities.ruleset:58
msgid ""
"Each entertainer produces two luxury good points for their city per turn, "
"increasing to three once any player has built Shakespeare's Theater. See the "
"section on Happiness for the effects of luxury good points."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/cities.ruleset:73 data/sandbox/cities.ruleset:73
msgid ""
"Each scientist adds two bulbs to your empire's research output per turn, "
"increasing to three once any player has built Darwin's Voyage."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/game.ruleset:26
#, fuzzy
msgid "Royale ruleset"
msgstr "_حذف تجهيز مسبق"

#. TRANS: In the client, this is displayed alongside the contents of
#. ;    README.royale, which are not localized.
#: data/royale/game.ruleset:40
msgid ""
"You are playing Freeciv21 with Royale ruleset based on Longturn Traditional "
"LTT rules (originally based on civ2civ3):\n"
"\n"
"Gameplay more similar to classic 4x empire building games, keeping it easy "
"to learn but challenging to master.\n"
"\n"
"Also suitable for single player, with AI less aggressive at start, but more "
"challenging at the end.\n"
"\n"
"The Royale ruleset is designed to be played without AI players and allows "
"very fast gameplay meaning that one game does not take too much time. For "
"similar gameplay with more turns look for the LTT ruleset. and it is "
"balanced to make the game interesting for both beginners and experienced "
"players. Everything comes with a cost. Even advancing more than your "
"opponent. This keeps it challenging and fair to everyone."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:77
msgid ""
"* Buildings and technologies do not require any upkeep.\n"
"* Each worked tile that gives more than 2 Food, Shield, or Trade will suffer "
"a -1 penalty, unless the city working it is celebrating. (Cities below size "
"3 will not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support up to 2 units for free. Further units each cost 1 "
"shield per turn.\n"
"* Military units do not cause unhappiness even when deployed aggressively.\n"
"* Military units impose martial law. Up to 3 military units inside a city "
"will each force 1 unhappy citizen to become content.\n"
"* You have no control over national budget. Half of the trade income is "
"simply lost to your economy (less if you have luxury-promoting buildings), "
"and the remainder all goes to luxuries. Conventional corruption increases "
"with distance from the capital (half as fast with knowledge of The "
"Corporation).\n"
"* Base production waste is 30%. This increases with distance from the "
"capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks.\n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or more."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:96
msgid ""
"Playing with Anarchy? \n"
"You do not usually want to play with Anarchy but you need to when there is a "
"need to switch the government. For these situations you may want to plan "
"your production so that you have some gold reserve before switching to "
"Anarchy and also not using that many trade tiles while in Anarchy. You may "
"also want to explore the options to make your cities to celebrate while in "
"Anarchy. This way you may be able to make your cities to celebrate when you "
"switch to your new government. If you have only some bulbs left from getting "
"the governent you want it may make sense to revolt early and complete the "
"research with scientists. This may be very useful especially when you switch "
"away from Tribalism or Despotism because you may get the desired government "
"a turn or two early."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:123
msgid ""
"Compared to Despotism, a Tribal economy is more shield-oriented. Its bonuses "
"to veterancy can be an advantage in wartime."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:126
msgid ""
"* Increases by half the chance of land units getting the next veteran level "
"after a battle.\n"
"* Each worked tile that gives more than 2 Food, Shield, or Trade will suffer "
"a -1 penalty, unless the city working it is celebrating. (Cities below size "
"3 will not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support up to 2 units for free. Further units each cost 1 "
"shield per turn.\n"
"* Unlike later governments, military units do not cause unhappiness even "
"when deployed aggressively.\n"
"* Military units impose martial law. Up to 3 military units inside a city "
"will each force 1 unhappy citizen to become content.\n"
"* Base corruption is 30% (the highest under any government). This increases "
"with distance from the capital (half as fast with knowledge of The "
"Corporation).\n"
"* There is no base level of production waste, but an increasing amount with "
"distance from the capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or more."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:145
msgid ""
"Playing with Tribal? \n"
"Tribal nations get more production and are able to maintain more units for "
"free. Tribal is a very good alternative for someone who is not planning to "
"go Monarchy first. Instead you may want to consider building Ħal Saflieni "
"Hypogeum in your capital city and also building the Pyramids as fast as "
"possible to that you will get rid of the -1 tile penalty related to Anarchy, "
"Despotism, and Tribalism. It will also make sense to revolt during the first "
"turn. This way you may lose less production because of Anarchy. If you play "
"well you will get the Pyramids around T15 - T20 and this will keep your "
"empire competive even until the mid game. The catch however is that you may "
"be too comfortable with the Tribalism and switch to another government too "
"late. This is why you may want to consider switching around T40 - T60. In "
"short Tribalism helps fast expansion more compared to Despotism."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:176
msgid ""
"* Your centers of government (cities with Palace and 2nd Palace) get a +75% "
"bonus to gold production.\n"
"* Each worked tile that gives more than 2 Food, Shield, or Trade will suffer "
"a -1 penalty, unless the city working it is celebrating. (Cities below size "
"3 will not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support up to 2 units for free. Further units each cost 1 "
"gold per turn.\n"
"* Unlike later governments, military units do not cause unhappiness even "
"when deployed aggressively.\n"
"* Military units impose martial law. Up to 20 military units inside a city "
"will each force 1 unhappy citizen to become content.\n"
"* Base corruption is 20%. This increases with distance from the capital "
"(half as fast with knowledge of The Corporation).\n"
"* Base production waste is 10%. This increases with distance from the "
"capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or more."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:194
msgid ""
"Playing with Despotism? \n"
"With Despotism you get slightly better science and if you plan to go for "
"Monarchy this may be your choice. Despotism is a very good alternative for "
"someone who is planning to go Monarchy first. While you may want to consider "
"building Ħal Saflieni Hypogeum in your capital city and also building the "
"Pyramids as fast as possible you may want to focus instead on maxing science "
"and using scientists for getting Monarchy really fast. In this case you may "
"want to build the Pyramids after revolting and switching to Monarchy or "
"maybe even Fudamentalism. Then again Despotism may be great if you need to "
"defend. It allows a crazy number of units to be used for keeping the people "
"content. This together with Pyramids is also great."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:224
msgid ""
"* Your centers of government (cities with Palace and 2nd Palace) get a +50% "
"bonus to gold production.\n"
"* Celebrating cities produce one extra trade point for every tile which is "
"already producing trade. (Cities below size 3 will not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support up to 3 units for free (the maximum possible). "
"Further units each cost 1 gold per turn.\n"
"* Each city tolerates up to 3 aggressively deployed military units. Each "
"further unit causes 1 unhappy citizen.\n"
"* Military units impose martial law. Up to 3 military units inside a city "
"will each force 1 unhappy citizen to become content.\n"
"* Base corruption is 10%. This increases with distance from the capital "
"(half as fast with knowledge of The Corporation).\n"
"* Base production waste is 10%. This increases with distance from the "
"capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or "
"more.  The number of units avoiding the military unhappiness will also "
"double at this size."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:242
msgid ""
"Playing with Monarchy? \n"
"Monarchy is great for those players who want to play war. You do not get "
"that much gold of production with Monarchy but instead it is reasonably good "
"for those players who want to attack, attack, and attack. In the late early "
"game and early mid game it is a good alternative also for those who wish to "
"build and not fight wars. Switching to Monarchy will remove the -1 penalty "
"you get from Anarchy, Despotism, and Tribalism and this will allow you to "
"ramp up your economy for the better governments to come. If you go for "
"Monarchy in the early game try to do it fast. Maybe using the scientists for "
"few turns and then getting the tech by T15 - T20. However, even the farmers "
"may want to stick with Monarchy for some time because of the great unit "
"upkeep for workers and less waste."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:275
msgid ""
"* City improvements which would normally have an upkeep of 1 gold are free "
"of upkeep.\n"
"* Each city can support up to 3 units for free (the maximum possible). "
"Further units each cost 1 shield per turn.\n"
"* Each city tolerates up to 3 aggressively deployed military units. Each "
"further unit causes 1 unhappy citizen.\n"
"* Military units impose martial law. Up to 3 military units inside a city "
"will each force 2 unhappy citizens to become content (the maximum "
"possible).\n"
"* Base corruption is 30%, but is not affected by distance to the capital.\n"
"* There is no production waste.\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or "
"more.  The number of units avoiding the military unhappiness will also "
"double at this size."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:290
msgid ""
"Playing with Communism? \n"
"Communistic nations are able to grow big, fast and they can have huge "
"production. The downside is that the gold production is low. If you manage "
"to get the Statue of Liberty it may make sense to switch to Communism really "
"fast. Also, if you have a vast empire and you are allied with someone who "
"has better techs, you may want to play as the commie leader."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:328
msgid ""
"* Base science production is 40% that of other governments. (A "
"Fundamentalist city with a Library produces roughly as much science as a "
"city under another government does alone.)\n"
"* Each city can support up to 2 units for free. Further units each cost 2 "
"gold per turn (except for Fanatics).\n"
"* Each city tolerates up to 2 aggressively deployed military units. Each "
"further unit causes 1 unhappy citizen.\n"
"* Base corruption is 15%. This increases with distance from the capital "
"(half as fast with knowledge of The Corporation).\n"
"* Base production waste is 15%. This increases with distance from the "
"capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or "
"more.  The number of units avoiding the military unhappiness will also "
"double at this size."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:343
msgid ""
"Playing with fundamentalism? \n"
"Fundamentalism is for a player who needs to build lots funda specific units "
"(Crusaders, Fanatics) fast. This may be useful if you are defending your "
"nation or buying some time to your ally while that other nation needs to "
"focus on something else. Funda can also be used as an alternative early "
"government if you need to get lots of gold fast. With the happiness "
"buildings Funda is like a money printing machine. Choosing this government "
"also makes sense if you plan to steal your techs while fosusing on building "
"infrastructure."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:371
msgid ""
"* Each city gets 2 extra luxury good points.\n"
"* Celebrating cities produce one extra trade point for every tile which is "
"already producing trade. (Cities below size 3 will not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support up to 2 units for free. Further units each cost 2 "
"gold per turn.\n"
"* Each city tolerates up to 2 aggressively deployed military units. Each "
"further unit causes 1 unhappy citizen.\n"
"* There is no base level of corruption, but an increasing amount with "
"distance from the capital (half as much as with most other governments). "
"Knowledge of The Corporation eliminates this corruption.\n"
"* Base production waste is 30%, but is not affected by distance to the "
"capital.\n"
"* Has a senate that may prevent declaration of war.\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or "
"more.  The number of units avoiding the military unhappiness will also "
"double at this size."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:388
msgid ""
"Playing with federation? \n"
"Federation may work as a boost for switching into Democracy. If you need to "
"research reasonably fast and there is less need for gold, it may make sense "
"to switch to Federation before you choose another form of govermnent. With "
"Federation you get a nice boost for your science while you are still able to "
"fight wars. However there is a catch to this. You may want to carefully "
"compare your advance to the nations with the other form of government. While "
"Federation receives a generous boost to science, in addition to other "
"bonuses, in the long term it will not be able to compete against "
"Democracies. This of course depends on the game you are playing but "
"typically 20 - 30 turns with Federation should be more than enough in the "
"mid game. After that you may want to quit fighting wars and focus on "
"something else or maybe switch to another government."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:421
msgid ""
"* Cities produce an extra trade point for every worked land tile that is "
"already producing trade.\n"
"* Celebrating cities produce a further trade point for every worked tile "
"(land or water) which is already producing trade. (Cities below size 3 will "
"not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support one unit for free. further units each cost 1 shield "
"per turn.\n"
"* Each city tolerates a single aggressively deployed military unit. Each "
"further unit causes 1 unhappy citizen.\n"
"* Base corruption is 25%. This increases with distance from the capital "
"(half as fast with knowledge of The Corporation).\n"
"* Base production waste is 20%. This increases with distance from the "
"capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or "
"more.  The number of units avoiding the military unhappiness will also "
"double at this size."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:438
msgid ""
"Playing with Republic? \n"
"Republic is the fast lane to Democracy and it is quite bad if you plan to "
"fight wars. Unlike with some other governments you can declare wars while in "
"Republic. This however comes with a hefty price unless you manage to keep "
"the wars extremely short or you crush a very weak enemy. Republics can "
"succeed if you have a very low number of units and you can afford to focus "
"on building Markets, Mercantile Exchanges, and Banks instead of military "
"units and huge numbers of workers. One of the best ways to succeed with a "
"Republic is to make peace or alliance with everyone around you and then "
"focus on ramping up your economy. Republic may also work better if your "
"cities have overlapping tiles. If you have little space for your empire it "
"may make sense to micromanage the worked tiles as Republic as your "
"government. This will allow you to reduce the number of workers since "
"overlapping city improvements will make it possible to use the same improved "
"tile for two or more cities. For example, when one city is about to grow "
"(currently getting +3 food) and needs +2 food you may switch a grassland "
"tile (irrigated, resource +1 production, and roads) to another city and use "
"a regular plans tile (irrigated, with roads) for the city only needing +2 "
"food. This way you do not produce +1 extra food going to waste and the other "
"city will benefit from the same worker tile. Like always there are many ways "
"to deal with the governments and another way to look at this is saying that "
"in Republic you can afford more buildings, while in Monarchy you can afford "
"more units. Going from Monarchy to Democracy is a popular route even while "
"in some situations adding Fedetation between them might make sense."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:480
msgid ""
"* Cities produce an extra trade point for every worked land tile that is "
"already producing trade.\n"
"* Celebrating cities produce a further trade point for every worked tile "
"(land or water) which is already producing trade. (Cities below size 3 will "
"not celebrate.)\n"
"* Each city can support one unit for free. Further units each cost 2 gold "
"per turn.\n"
"* Each city tolerates a single aggressively deployed military unit. Each "
"further unit causes 2 unhappy citizens.\n"
"* Base corruption is 5%. This increases with distance from the capital (half "
"as fast with knowledge of The Corporation).\n"
"* Base production waste is 25%. This increases with distance from the "
"capital (half as fast with knowledge of Trade).\n"
"* Has a senate that may prevent declaration of war.\n"
"* Big cities with size of 9 or more will get an extra 50 % defense against "
"military attacks. \n"
"* The number of free units will be doubled for cities with size of 9 or "
"more.  Unlike with other governments, the number of units avoiding the "
"military unhappiness will NOT be doubled at this size."
msgstr ""

#: data/royale/governments.ruleset:498
#, c-format
msgid ""
"Playing with Democracy? \n"
"Playing with a Democracy is probably the most effective way of creating a "
"super power, but this comes with a price. Unlike with some other setups "
"Democracies are quite vulnerable while the player is ramping up the economy. "
"The most common reason to have Democracy as your form of goverment is to "
"build an extremely powerful economy that will simply crush those nations "
"daring to act against your happy Democracy with you as its eternal leader. "
"If you are not planning to fight wars and you can afford to build Markets "
"and other trade related buildings, Democracy is probably the best choice you "
"can make. With Democracy you will get the best possible effect for compound "
"interest and if you manage to make your cities to celebrate this effect is "
"even more powerful. Democracies are able to maintain a decent army and lots "
"of workers. One very powerful strategy for you to consider is to switch "
"between max tax and max sci. If you are confident enough you may want to "
"delay scientific advance and focus on max taxing so that your economy will "
"grow really fast. There is however a catch to this. If you postpone "
"researching too much your enemy may be able to surprise you and your "
"outdated army. With a democatic nation it is also extremely important to "
"keep your citizens not only content but happy and celebrating. Celebration "
"gives you +1 extra trade for each tile already producing trade if you manage "
"to keep your cities celebrating. On some other setups using more than "
"20% luxury is usually considered bad but with Royale's trade building setup "
"it may be worth celebrating even with +40% luxury. It all depends on the "
"situiation, but it may be worth it if you manage to avoid building some "
"happiness buildings on the new cities while focusing the resources on the "
"big and old cities producing most of your gold. Also, if you are attacked or "
"need to fight wars it may make sense to home some units on the low "
"production cities. That way if those units cause unhappiness they will do it "
"for those cities that matter less to you. "
msgstr ""

